04324nam a22005655i 9780300143553DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20181998ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001435537 a10.12987/97803001435532doi  a(DE-B1597)486829  a(OCoLC)861792759  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aBIO0070002bisacsh04a811/.52222/eng1 aNepomnyashchy, Catharine Theimer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMan from Babel /cCatharine Theimer Nepomnyashchy. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2018] 4c©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on the Text -- tPrologue -- t1. European Frontier World -- t2. Immigrant into Neo-American -- t3. Roving Reporter -- t4. Return to the Old World -- t5. Reporter in Paris -- t6. Voyages of Discovery -- t7. Quest for New Words -- t8. Gog and Magog -- t9. Ananke Strikes the Poet -- t10. In the Maelstrom -- t11. Journey Through Rubbleland -- t12. News from Babel -- t13. The Frontierless World -- tEpilogue -- tNotes to Front Matter -- tNotes to Man from Babel -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe autobiography of Eugene Jolas, available for the first time nearly half a century after his death in 1952, is the story of a man who, as the editor of the expatriate American literary magazine transition, was the first publisher of James Joyce’s Finnegans Wake and other signal works of the modernist period. Jolas’s memoir provides often comical and compelling details about such leading modernist figures as Joyce, Stein, Hemingway, Breton, and Gide, and about the political, aesthetic, and social concerns of the Surrealists, Expressionists, and other literary figures during the 1920s and 1930s. Man from Babel both enriches and challenges our view of international modernism and the historical avant-garde.Born in New Jersey of immigrant parents, Jolas moved back to France with them at the age of two. He grew up in the borderland of Lorraine and later lived in Paris, Berlin, London, and New York, where he pursued a career as a journalist and aspiring poet. As an American press officer after the war, Jolas was actively involved in the denazification of German intellectual life. A champion of the international avant-garde, he continually sought translinguistic, transcultural, and suprapolitical bridges that would transform Western culture into a unified continuum.Compiled and edited from Jolas’s drafts and illustrated with contemporary photographs, this memoir not only reveals the multicultural concerns of the man from Babel, as Jolas saw himself, but also illuminates an entire literary and historical era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJournalistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aPoets, Americany20th centuryvBiography. 0aTranslatorszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030007536640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014355340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300143553423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300143553/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY